\details{
A Node.js-style event-driven base for long-lived WebSocket streams (any
long-lived push feed). You register handlers with
\verb{$on(event, handler)} — exactly like \code{ws.on("message", ...)} in JavaScript —
and the library calls them as messages arrive on R's event loop (the \code{later}
package, which, like Node, is built on libuv). Concrete connectors subclass
it and override two seams — \code{.dispatch()} (how a raw frame becomes events) and
\code{.resubscribe()} (what to re-send after a (re)connect) — getting all of the
reconnect / keepalive / watchdog machinery for free.
\subsection{Why no \code{async} flag (unlike a REST client)}{

A REST call has a single result, so it can return a value (sync) or a promise
(async). A socket is an endless push stream with no single result, so the only
sensible shape is a callback. Streams are therefore always event-driven; the
one thing R needs that Node gives for free is a way to keep the process alive
and pump the loop — that is \verb{$run()}.
}

\subsection{Events}{

The set is \strong{open} — \verb{$on(event, ...)} accepts any string, and a subclass'
\code{.dispatch()} may \code{emit} its own (e.g. one event per message type). The base
emits a standard core:
\itemize{
\item \code{"open"} — the socket connected (payload: the open event).
\item \code{"message"} — the default \code{.dispatch()} emits this for every frame, carrying
the message as a \strong{character string} (binary frames are decoded with
\code{\link[=rawToChar]{rawToChar()}} first, so a handler always gets text).
\item \code{"close"} / \code{"error"} — the socket closed / errored (payload: the event).
\item \code{"reconnecting"} — about to retry (payload: \code{list(attempt, delay)}).
\item \code{"reconnected"} — a reconnect (not the first connect) succeeded.
\item \code{"giveup"} — \code{max_reconnects} exhausted; the \verb{$run()} loop will exit.
\item \code{"stale"} — the silence watchdog fired (no frame within \code{stale_timeout}).
}
}

\subsection{Connection management (handled for you)}{
\itemize{
\item \strong{Auto-reconnect} with full-jitter exponential backoff, so a reconnect
storm cannot trip a connection rate limit.
\item \strong{Silence watchdog} — if \code{stale_timeout} is set and no frame arrives within
it, the socket is force-closed and reopened (a dead connection that never
fired \code{onClose}).
\item \strong{Proactive reconnect} — if \code{proactive_reconnect} is set, reconnect that
many seconds after opening (e.g. to beat a server's 24-hour forced cutoff).
\item \strong{Re-subscribe} after every (re)connect via the \code{.resubscribe()} hook.
\item \strong{Keepalive} keeps one task on the \code{later} queue so a host-driven
\verb{while (!later::loop_empty())} loop never exits early between frames.
}
}
}
